rica and the world. And yet After Katrina also suggests that New Orleans culture offers a way of thinking about the United States in terms that transcend the binary of national renewal or declension. The post-Hurricane city thus emerges as a flashpoint for reflecting on the contemporary United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditionsxLouisianaxNew Orleans. 0aAfrican AmericanszLouisianazNew Orleans (La.)xSocial conditions. 0aCapitalismxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aCapitalismxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aEnvironmental policyxUnited States. 0aEnvironmental policyzUnited States. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005xSocial aspectsxLouisianaxNew Orleans. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005xSocial aspectszLouisianazNew Orleans. 0aNeoliberalismxUnited States. 0aNeoliberalismzUnited States. 0aSocial changexUnited States. 0aSocial changezUnited States. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Postcolonial Studies. 4aHistory : American History. 4aSociology : Urban Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / 21st Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2017z978311149102840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438464190423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438464190/original  a978-3-11-149102-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles